<section xml:id="sec-long-run-behavior-of-rationals" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Long-Run Behavior of Rational Functions</title>

  <p>
    In this section, we will concern ourselves with the <em>long-run behavior</em> of rational functions.

  </p>

  <p>
    Consider the graph of the function
    
    <me>
        f(x)=\frac{2x(x+1)}{(x+2)(x-1)}
    </me>
    
  </p>

<figure>
    <image width="60%">
        <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="long-run-rational-function">
            <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
            <definition>f(x)=(2*x*(x+1))/((x+2)*(x-1))</definition>
                <coordinates bbox="(-6,-4,6,4)">
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="f" domain="(-7.5,-2.0001)"/>
                    <graph function="f" domain="(-1.999,0.999)"/>
                    <graph function="f" domain="(1.0001,7.2)"/>
                </coordinates>
            </diagram>
        </prefigure>
    </image>
</figure>

<p>
    Just like with polynomial functions, we can imagine zooming way out on the graph, and we want a way to describe what the far left and far right ends of the graph are doing.
</p>

<figure>
    <image width="60%">
        <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="long-run-rational-function-zoom-in">
            <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
            <definition>f(x)=(2*x*(x+1))/((x+2)*(x-1))</definition>
                <coordinates bbox="(-100,-5,100,5)">
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="f" domain="(-100,-2.0001)"/>
                    <graph function="f" domain="(-1.999,0.999)"/>
                    <graph function="f" domain="(1.0001,100)"/>
                </coordinates>
            </diagram>
        </prefigure>
    </image>
</figure>

<p>
    This shows us that, when our <m>x</m>-values become very large and negative, our <m>y</m>-values become very close to <m>2</m>, and when our <m>x</m>-values become very large and positive, our <m>y</m>-values become very close to <m>2</m> as well.
</p>

<p>
    Using our symbolic end behavior notation, we can write this as

    <me>
        \text{As } x \rightarrow -\infty, f(x) \rightarrow 2
    </me>

    and

    <me>
        \text{As } x \rightarrow \infty, f(x) \rightarrow 2.
    </me>
    
</p>

<p>
    But why does this happen? Let's revisit our function's equation:

    <me>
        f(x)=\frac{2x(x+1)}{(x+2)(x-1)}
    </me>

    If we multiply out the numerator and the denominator of the function, we can rewrite the function as

    <me>
        f(x)=\frac{2x^2+2x}{x^2+x-2}
    </me>
    
</p>

</section>
